AU: Gamo, T; Tsutsumi, M; Sakai, H; Nakazawa, T; Tanaka, M; Honda, H; Kubo, H; Itoh, T
AF: Gamo, Toshitaka; Tsutsumi, Makoto; Sakai, Hitoshi; Nakazawa, Takakiyo; Tanaka, Masayuki; Honda, Hideyuki; Kubo, Haruya; Itoh, Tomizo
TI: Carbon and oxygen isotopic ratios of carbon dioxide of a stratospheric profile over Japan
SO: TELLUS SERIES B-CHEMICAL AND PHYSICAL METEOROLOGY
AB: Four stratospheric air samples from 19 to 25 km altitudes over Japan were collected by using a balloon-borne cryogenic sampling system to measure the vertical profiles of carbon and oxygen stable isotopic ratios of the lower stratospheric CO(2). The delta(13)C value of the stratospheric CO(2) increased with increasing altitude, while the CO(2) mixing ratios decreased, in accordance with anthropogenic input of the isotopically light, fuel CO(2) into the atmosphere. However, the relationship between delta(13)C and CO(2) mixing ratio (-0.07 parts per thousand ppmv(-1)) was somehow similar to that for the seasonal variation in the troposphere rather than that for the secular variation so far observed in the troposphere (-0.02 similar to -0.03 parts per thousand ppmv(-1)). The delta(18)O of the stratospheric CO(2) was found to be about 2 parts per thousand greater than that of the tropospheric CO(2) at an altitude of 19 km and to increase further with increasing altitude. Two possibilities for explaining this phenomenon are presented and discussed. One possibility is that the tropical CO(2) with high delta(18)O might upwell and advect horizontally to the midlatitudinal stratosphere, although the delta(18)O enhancement by this process is insufficient to raise the delta(18)O value up to the observed level. The other is that the (18)O might be enriched by an in-situ oxygen isotope exchange between CO(2) and O(2), which is possibly accelerated through photochemical dissociations of O(2) and CO(2). A relationship between delta(18)O of CO(2) and (18)O enrichment of ozone in the stratosphere is also suggested.
